00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:26.700
[Amit Varma]: And now, let's move on to the show.

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:29.460
[Amit Varma]: One speaks of India's great demographic dividend.

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:31.740
[Amit Varma]: The average age in India is 27.

00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:37.460
[Amit Varma]: 60% of this country was born after 1991, the year in which we allegedly liberalized some

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:38.820
[Amit Varma]: of our economy.

00:01:38.820 --> 00:01:41.460
[Amit Varma]: Our young people should be our greatest asset.

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:46.020
[Amit Varma]: And yet, our young people need jobs and education, and these are just not there.

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:50.140
[Amit Varma]: Every month, one million people enter the workforce, and there just aren't enough jobs

00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:51.140
[Amit Varma]: for them.

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:55.220
[Amit Varma]: All of these young people, entering the best years of their lives with hope and desire,

00:01:55.220 --> 00:01:57.100
[Amit Varma]: but without opportunities.

00:01:57.100 --> 00:01:58.280
[Amit Varma]: What are they to do?

00:01:58.280 --> 00:01:59.860
[Amit Varma]: How do they feel about this?

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:01.820
[Amit Varma]: Can they be anything but angry?

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:03.660
[Amit Varma]: How do they cope with their anger?

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:09.660
[Amit Varma]: Will this so-called demographic dividend end up being a demographic disaster?

00:02:09.660 --> 00:02:17.580
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:18.580
[Unknown]: science.

00:02:18.580 --> 00:02:20.820
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:23.620
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:02:23.620 --> 00:02:28.380
[Amit Varma]: As a middle-aged man of great privilege, living in a big city, I sometimes feel I don't understand

00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:29.980
[Amit Varma]: what India is all about.

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:35.020
[Amit Varma]: The life I live as a member of the elite is very different from the lives lived by most

00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:36.300
[Amit Varma]: of my fellow Indians.

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:40.700
[Amit Varma]: And I wonder sometimes in my little cocoon whether I understand this country at all.

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:42.380
[Amit Varma]: So much about it is so bewildering.

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:46.900
[Amit Varma]: Well, my guest on today's episode is someone who has helped clear some of the fog from

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:47.900
[Amit Varma]: my head.

00:02:47.900 --> 00:02:52.740
[Amit Varma]: Snigdha Poonam is a Delhi-based journalist, and her book, Dreamers, chronicles the lives

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:57.660
[Amit Varma]: of a handful of young Indians and gives a sense of how young people across small towns

00:02:57.660 --> 00:03:00.540
[Amit Varma]: in North India feel about the world.

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:02.860
[Amit Varma]: Reading the book was an interesting experience to me.

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:07.220
[Amit Varma]: The characters and the way they thought about the world seemed very familiar to me.

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:12.140
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, the world they inhabited and the way they chose to behave in that world

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:13.140
[Amit Varma]: felt surreal.

00:03:13.140 --> 00:03:18.380
[Amit Varma]: Snigdha's book gave me an acute sense of the many parallel universes that exist within

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:22.820
[Amit Varma]: this one nation of ours, and I'm delighted that she's agreed to join me in the studio

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:27.780
[Amit Varma]: today, to talk about her experience of writing this book and the insights she gained from

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:28.780
[Amit Varma]: it.

