[Amit Varma]: Thank you, Amit.

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:28.340
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how you decided to write this book to begin with.

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:30.980
[Amit Varma]: How did the idea of the book come to you?

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:33.940
[Guest]: Started on a dating website.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:40.140
[Guest]: Back in the day, I think 2009, an American dating website has just entered the Indian

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:41.140
[Guest]: market.

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:45.580
[Guest]: You know, I mean, this was the time that everyone was talking about like India's hundreds of

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:48.300
[Guest]: millions of people joining the middle class.

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:53.500
[Guest]: So it was just natural that something of that kind would, you know, would tap into that

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:54.500
[Guest]: market.

00:04:54.500 --> 00:05:00.380
[Guest]: So this website comes to India, and suddenly, everyone's on it.

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:05.700
[Guest]: And I read a couple of pieces just announcing its arrival and its popularity, and I signed

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:13.500
[Guest]: up for a long form piece for the Caravan magazine, where I was working then.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:21.260
[Guest]: I signed up, and I made a very basic profile, which is just, you know, age, location, hobbies,

00:05:21.260 --> 00:05:22.260
[Guest]: etc.

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:27.380
[Guest]: Put a very basic photo of myself and just like, let it out.

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:35.300
[Guest]: And I wake up the next morning, and I have hundreds of messages from young men, like,

00:05:35.300 --> 00:05:39.300
[Guest]: you know, from 18 to, I would say, 32, 33.

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:41.700
[Guest]: That wasn't so surprising to me.

00:05:41.700 --> 00:05:46.140
[Guest]: I expected some of that, I mean, not so many, but I expected some of that.

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:50.980
[Guest]: But what surprised me that not all of these messages were, you know, these like young

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:55.020
[Guest]: men declaring love or wanting to have sex with me or saying hi, baby, or the sort of

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:57.900
[Guest]: stuff that that usually comes in.

00:05:57.900 --> 00:06:02.340
[Guest]: A lot of these people, and I started responding to some of them wanted to just talk to me

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:07.420
[Guest]: about about their lives, because no one was talking to them.

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:10.140
[Guest]: And I was a woman, I was real, I was talking to them.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:17.180
[Guest]: And they were in the smallest of, you know, places in the, like, most obscure corners

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:23.300
[Guest]: in India, places that I've never heard of, like villages in Andhra Pradesh, and Northeast

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:27.260
[Guest]: and Tamil Nadu, and of course, UP and Bihar and the usual.

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:32.940
[Guest]: And some of them were telling me the same things, which is that, which is like a deep

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:35.820
[Guest]: feeling of frustration with where their lives were.

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:40.780
[Guest]: And with whatever prospects that, you know, stretched out in front of them, they were,

00:06:40.780 --> 00:06:43.700
[Guest]: if they were in college, they didn't know if they were going to get jobs.

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:48.620
[Guest]: If they were already working, they weren't satisfied with their income, if they will

00:06:48.620 --> 00:06:52.700
[Guest]: live with their family, they didn't know if they were fitting in, if their parents understood

00:06:52.700 --> 00:06:58.020
[Guest]: them, they, most of them wanted to get out and make something of their lives, but didn't

00:06:58.020 --> 00:06:59.620
[Guest]: know how.

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:04.220
[Guest]: And I mean, sure, there was a lot of anxiety about love and sex and romance.

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:06.340
[Guest]: And I did write about that, too.

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:07.860
[Guest]: But this stayed with me.

00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:11.340
[Guest]: And I started thinking about that more deeply.

00:07:11.340 --> 00:07:14.580
[Guest]: And but I just remained on the website and let these messages come.

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:21.820
[Guest]: And then shortly after that, I wrote another story that took me back into the same world.

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:24.020
[Guest]: This was something for the New York Times.

00:07:24.020 --> 00:07:29.980
[Guest]: And I, I used to keep getting these, like, messages like spam, I'm sure everyone did,

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:33.040
[Guest]: and still does, about this personality development classes.

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:36.180
[Guest]: This was at least a huge rage in Delhi.

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:40.060
[Guest]: So every day I would wake up and I had these messages saying, you can develop your personality

00:07:40.060 --> 00:07:48.060
[Guest]: for 2500 rupees a month come to this, like London School of English in Atparganj or somewhere

00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:49.460
[Guest]: or the other.

00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:54.140
[Guest]: And so one day, I just decided to show up because I was like, what is this personality?

00:07:54.140 --> 00:07:56.780
[Guest]: And you know, who needs personality?

00:07:56.780 --> 00:07:59.740
[Guest]: In what way is it being developed?

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:04.220
[Guest]: So I show up at a one of these like London School of English classes in Rajouri Garden.

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:11.340
[Guest]: And again, it is crowded with like, the same kind of people who were speaking to me from

00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:12.900
[Guest]: across India on the dating website.

00:08:12.900 --> 00:08:20.060
[Guest]: These were some very young men, I'm talking 17, 18, they had come to Delhi from small

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:25.780
[Guest]: towns and villages and because this was Delhi, Rajasthan and Haryana and UP.

00:08:25.780 --> 00:08:29.820
[Guest]: And they were all either just out of college or had dropped out and were all looking for

00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:35.500
[Guest]: opportunities in Delhi, and just didn't know how to be in a big city, how to, how to, you

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:41.140
[Guest]: know, talk to people, how to face an interview, how to approach a girl, that sort of thing,

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:44.980
[Guest]: you know, how to order things at a restaurant or, or talk to someone in a bus.

00:08:44.980 --> 00:08:50.900
[Guest]: So that this was like, they were looking for to develop a more global personality and,

00:08:50.900 --> 00:08:51.900
[Guest]: and how does it start?

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:56.020
[Guest]: And this, they, you know, it was basically a class in spoken English.

00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:58.300
[Guest]: So it begins with an introduction, where are you from?

00:08:58.300 --> 00:08:59.300
[Guest]: What do you want to do?

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:00.660
[Guest]: What are your hobbies?

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:06.420
[Guest]: And, and then like, you know, goes like pretty deep, pretty quickly.

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:11.580
[Guest]: And I, and I got to that later in the spoken English chapter for the book.

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:14.540
[Guest]: So you know, some of these themes were coming up.

00:09:14.540 --> 00:09:22.260
[Guest]: And I had done three or four of these stories, when a penguin random house got in touch with

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:28.860
[Guest]: me and said that they had an idea, they wanted me to go back to my own small town, Ranchi,

00:09:28.860 --> 00:09:33.380
[Guest]: and just be there for a while, at least at least a year, start talking to people, choose

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:36.580
[Guest]: some of them and see what they want from their lives.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:41.700
[Guest]: And if you know, in the time that I'm following them, if they'll get any like anywhere close

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:44.520
[Guest]: to those, those dreams and desires.

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:50.580
[Amit Varma]: And like, what kind of preconceived notions did you go in with, which sort of turned out

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:54.540
[Amit Varma]: to not be the case when you went and what did you really learn through this process?

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:57.740
[Amit Varma]: How different is your eventual book from what you thought it would be?

00:09:57.740 --> 00:09:59.580
[Amit Varma]: What did you think you would find which you did not?

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:04.300
[Guest]: I mean, honestly, I didn't know anything, which is hard for people to realize.

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:10.420
[Guest]: But I grew up in a cocoon of cocoons in small towns in North India, because my father was

00:10:10.420 --> 00:10:16.540
[Guest]: a senior bureaucrat, and we always had a whole like system of like, you know, walls and boundaries

00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:22.780
[Guest]: around us and think that as, as a girl who's growing up in an upper middle class family

00:10:22.780 --> 00:10:28.820
[Guest]: in a bureaucratic setup, most avoid are like just young men on the loose.

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:32.260
[Guest]: And I, I just avoided them growing up.

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:37.220
[Guest]: And so I didn't know what like, you know, young men in North Indian villages and small

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:39.700
[Guest]: towns actually think and feel.

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:44.140
[Guest]: So it was, first of all, a challenge for me to like, go back and engage with that group

00:10:44.140 --> 00:10:49.260
[Guest]: of people that I had, you know, done my best to avoid growing up.

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:50.860
[Guest]: So I didn't have that many notions.

00:10:50.860 --> 00:10:55.780
[Guest]: I mean, I read the usual stuff that we all do, I knew that there was like a great wave

00:10:55.780 --> 00:11:02.300
[Guest]: of aspiration, because that kept coming up, that people want big, shiny, fancy things.

00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:04.740
[Guest]: And that, you know, small towns were like changing.

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:10.260
[Guest]: And there was suddenly like gyms and spas and hotels and restaurants.

00:11:10.260 --> 00:11:16.260
[Guest]: But beyond that, I, I don't think that my understanding was at all extensive.

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:20.660
[Amit Varma]: And there's a very interesting sentence in your first chapter where you, you write a

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:24.140
[Amit Varma]: couple of evocative paragraphs about your growing up as a small town girl.

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:28.180
[Amit Varma]: And there you say, at one point, that quote, I was fortunate to become a thinking adult

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:30.460
[Amit Varma]: before post truth, unquote.

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:34.820
[Amit Varma]: So it's not just as if when you were in these small towns, you had kind of stayed in your

00:11:34.820 --> 00:11:35.820
[Amit Varma]: cocoon.

00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:37.180
[Amit Varma]: And now you went back and went beyond that.

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:41.540
[Amit Varma]: But also the times had changed fundamentally that the young men who grew up at the same

00:11:41.540 --> 00:11:45.740
[Amit Varma]: time as you would not be the same as these young men you were now speaking to, who were

00:11:45.740 --> 00:11:49.780
[Amit Varma]: growing up in an India where sort of there were so many more young people, there were

00:11:49.780 --> 00:11:51.500
[Amit Varma]: so many more globalized influences.

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:54.620
[Guest]: Yes, they had so much more information and opinion.

00:11:54.620 --> 00:11:57.920
[Guest]: And yes, I didn't expect that either.

00:11:57.920 --> 00:12:02.500
[Amit Varma]: And I was very sort of struck by like a couple of the insights that come through your book

00:12:02.500 --> 00:12:05.940
[Amit Varma]: is that everybody feels so incredibly entitled.

00:12:05.940 --> 00:12:10.460
[Amit Varma]: And you said the further you go away from the cities, the bigger these young people

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:11.460
[Amit Varma]: think.

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:14.260
[Amit Varma]: So there is a sense of entitlement that I want to be great in the case of one of your

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:15.260
[Amit Varma]: protagonists.

00:12:15.260 --> 00:12:20.940
[Amit Varma]: He wants to not just be prime minister, but eventually rule Mars after those guys go there.

00:12:20.940 --> 00:12:25.780
[Amit Varma]: And along with this entitlement, there's also a lot of anger because those things aren't

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:26.860
[Amit Varma]: really happening.

00:12:26.860 --> 00:12:30.380
[Amit Varma]: And at one level, it seems to me that these are sort of ingrained emotions.

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:33.860
[Amit Varma]: Young people everywhere tend to be like, I remember I was very entitled and angry when

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:34.980
[Amit Varma]: I was young.

00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:39.880
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, there seems to be a sense in your book that there is something

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:45.260
[Amit Varma]: different about the sense of entitlement that these guys feel, especially, for example,

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:51.100
[Amit Varma]: in the inside that the more you go towards small towns, the more you will find this.

00:12:51.100 --> 00:12:52.100
[Amit Varma]: Why is that the case?

00:12:52.100 --> 00:12:53.100
[Guest]: No, you're right.

00:12:53.100 --> 00:12:56.980
[Guest]: I mean, I remember being a very ambitious young woman myself.

00:12:56.980 --> 00:13:03.980
[Guest]: But I think that what has changed is that, you know, no matter where they are, like what

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:08.260
[Guest]: they're facing, what they're looking at, you know, the message that comes to them constantly

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:10.380
[Guest]: is that anything is possible.

00:13:10.380 --> 00:13:14.380
[Guest]: You know, from I was listening to some of the Narendra Modi's speeches from 2014, he

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:18.900
[Guest]: actually speaks to them like a motivational speaker would.

00:13:18.900 --> 00:13:20.260
[Guest]: He speaks about dreams.

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:21.260
[Guest]: He brings that up.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:25.900
[Guest]: He says that their potential is being wasted, you know, that all of these like years of

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:30.580
[Guest]: opportunities have just like gone by and that, you know, that you dream and we will make

00:13:30.580 --> 00:13:31.780
[Guest]: it possible sort of thing.

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:35.100
[Guest]: You know, you'll be listening to ads, you can be on the Internet.

00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:42.540
[Guest]: I mean, so I think that it is very hard for a 19 year old in a village in Jharkhand to

00:13:42.540 --> 00:13:48.340
[Guest]: be totally disconnected and not internalize any of these like several messages that filter

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:51.100
[Guest]: down to him on a daily basis.

00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:54.940
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the backdrop of all this, a backdrop of what is happening in young India

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:59.460
[Amit Varma]: today, so to say, and the backdrop of your whole book is what you call India's 3E problem,

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:03.500
[Amit Varma]: which is that people are uneducated, unemployed and unemployable.

00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:08.260
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, the first and the third, uneducated and unemployable are part of the same thing.

00:14:08.260 --> 00:14:13.420
[Amit Varma]: And even many educated people are unemployable because of the state of our education system.

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:20.660
[Amit Varma]: And your book really sort of divides the responses to this into these three sections where your

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:26.140
[Amit Varma]: first section is about how some people try to mitigate this and find opportunity in different

00:14:26.140 --> 00:14:27.140
[Amit Varma]: ways.

00:14:27.140 --> 00:14:31.580
[Amit Varma]: Your second section is about the enormous amount of anger out there and how that finds

00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:36.540
[Amit Varma]: expression and the third section of your book is about and which I want to ask you about

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:41.540
[Amit Varma]: in detail later about how we have this mentality that the only way to get ahead is by scamming

00:14:41.540 --> 00:14:42.900
[Amit Varma]: other people.

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:46.660
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of talk section by section in the first chapter of your book.

00:14:46.660 --> 00:14:51.740
[Amit Varma]: It was it's called the click baiter and it's this about this fascinating chap called Vinay

00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:56.420
[Amit Varma]: Singhal and this company that he built called witty feed, which is, you know, you mentioned

00:14:56.420 --> 00:15:00.380
[Amit Varma]: was number two in the world after BuzzFeed in terms of viral content.

00:15:00.380 --> 00:15:05.300
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost as confluence of circumstances, which like a perfect storm which created them.

00:15:05.300 --> 00:15:09.260
[Amit Varma]: Number one, he was a man with big dreams and like you mentioned before, quote, it almost

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:13.460
[Amit Varma]: seemed as if the further you live from a big city, the bigger your dreams, unquote.

00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:17.500
[Amit Varma]: Second, he chose to go to indoor and set up this company.

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:21.240
[Amit Varma]: And again, you say in your book, quote, the city was big enough to be full of young job

00:15:21.240 --> 00:15:26.300
[Amit Varma]: aspirants and small enough to present them with few options, unquote, and therefore fertile

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:28.940
[Amit Varma]: ground for him to find people to work with him.

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:32.980
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting how he hired all these young people with the condition that

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:35.980
[Amit Varma]: this would be absolutely the first job.

00:15:35.980 --> 00:15:41.660
[Amit Varma]: And they were expected to immerse themselves in cultures which they knew nothing about

00:15:41.660 --> 00:15:44.820
[Amit Varma]: and create content which would be compelling content for them.

00:15:44.820 --> 00:15:48.660
[Amit Varma]: Like you describe a girl who's never dated in her life, who's 18 years old, who's creating

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:53.540
[Amit Varma]: content about what to do if you're jilted or so on and so forth.

00:15:53.540 --> 00:15:56.700
[Amit Varma]: And there's another really nice sentence in the book about this where you say, quote,

00:15:56.700 --> 00:16:00.580
[Amit Varma]: a week at the company is all it takes them to go from not knowing anything about the

00:16:00.580 --> 00:16:05.100
[Amit Varma]: world to deciding what the world should know.

00:16:05.100 --> 00:16:06.100
[Amit Varma]: Full stop.

00:16:06.100 --> 00:16:09.220
[Amit Varma]: And you've actually seen these people, they all live in a couple of bungalows together

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:14.180
[Amit Varma]: and so on, and it's like a family, like you mentioned, the way they where they work.

00:16:14.180 --> 00:16:16.260
[Amit Varma]: And I found this whole ecosystem very fascinating.

00:16:16.260 --> 00:16:19.100
[Amit Varma]: And also, how the hell could they succeed?

00:16:19.100 --> 00:16:22.660
[Amit Varma]: Because they literally didn't know anything about the people they were writing for.

00:16:22.660 --> 00:16:23.660
[Guest]: Yes.

00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:27.620
[Guest]: I mean, I guess I, I said at some point in the chapter that this was like the first time

00:16:27.620 --> 00:16:32.540
[Guest]: I had met a set of people who lived in the internet.

00:16:32.540 --> 00:16:38.100
[Guest]: So you know, they, everything that they know about the world is from the internet as the

00:16:38.100 --> 00:16:43.820
[Guest]: man himself, Vinay Singhal, told me in one of his thoughtful monologues.

00:16:43.820 --> 00:16:49.500
[Guest]: He said that the internet is the most powerful tool that, you know, the man has ever invented.

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:54.300
[Guest]: And I was blown away by it because there have been other tools.

00:16:54.300 --> 00:17:00.220
[Guest]: But you know, you take an 18 year old, and she's, you know, writing an article about

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:03.340
[Guest]: how to build a swimming pool in your own house.

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:08.660
[Guest]: And I really wonder if that like comes from her own experiences, because she talks to

00:17:08.660 --> 00:17:14.460
[Guest]: me about her family and where she lives, you know, in one rented room in Indore with her

00:17:14.460 --> 00:17:20.060
[Guest]: mother and sister who've come from Gwalior to join her because of that passed away and

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:23.780
[Guest]: they would have left with nothing and she figured out about this company and she applied

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:24.860
[Guest]: for a job.

00:17:24.860 --> 00:17:29.460
[Guest]: And so now she has to like give Americans all sorts of life hacks for all sorts of problems

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:34.220
[Guest]: when she does not know a thing about America or Americans or American like suburban life

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:35.860
[Guest]: and its challenges.

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:39.940
[Guest]: But she learns everything on the internet.

00:17:39.940 --> 00:17:43.820
[Guest]: And so you know, she writes an article about how to build a swimming pool in your own house

00:17:43.820 --> 00:17:49.580
[Guest]: and at least like, you know, 1.5 million people would have read it.

00:17:49.580 --> 00:17:51.100
[Guest]: So, so that works.

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:52.260
[Amit Varma]: It's a great headline.

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:55.220
[Amit Varma]: I think I click on anything which offered to show me how to build a swimming pool in

00:17:55.220 --> 00:17:56.540
[Guest]: my own apartment in Bombay.

00:17:56.540 --> 00:18:02.060
[Guest]: No, I did click on how you've been brushing your teeth wrong all your life.

00:18:02.060 --> 00:18:03.060
[Amit Varma]: And have you?

00:18:03.060 --> 00:18:04.060
[Amit Varma]: All of us.

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:08.060
[Amit Varma]: Okay, I don't want to go and look for that story.

00:18:08.060 --> 00:18:12.300
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, and what kind of struck me what you mentioned about living in the internet

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:17.900
[Amit Varma]: is that as much as they were living in India, they were also living in Americana, in a sense.

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:22.220
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, it's almost wrong to say that she would not know what it is like to have

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:23.900
[Amit Varma]: a swimming pool in her own house.

00:18:23.900 --> 00:18:28.780
[Guest]: Because yes, that is true in India, but in her virtual life on the internet, she's kind

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:30.220
[Guest]: of been through that.

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:35.780
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, you wake up and literally the first thing you have to think of on your own,

00:18:35.780 --> 00:18:40.660
[Guest]: I mean, with the help of the internet is you know, how to get lips like Kylie Jenner and

00:18:40.660 --> 00:18:46.620
[Guest]: at least I knew who Kylie Jenner was, but like several people don't and, and that was

00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:47.620
[Guest]: amazing to me.

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:51.780
[Guest]: And the thing is that I, what I want people to know is that this is not just these like

00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:53.380
[Guest]: 80 kids in Indore.

00:18:53.380 --> 00:18:57.740
[Guest]: I've met so many people like that when I was not reporting on WittyFeed, I was hanging

00:18:57.740 --> 00:19:02.860
[Guest]: out with an Instagram with a friend of mine who is an Instagram friend of mine from Indore.

00:19:02.860 --> 00:19:07.460
[Guest]: She was, she's 18, she was in college, and we became friends because she was fashion

00:19:07.460 --> 00:19:08.460
[Guest]: blogging on Instagram.

00:19:08.460 --> 00:19:12.500
[Guest]: And I was like interested in very young fashion bloggers in small towns who were actually

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:14.560
[Guest]: making money off this.

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:19.460
[Guest]: So I spent a couple of days in her hostel room in Indore.

00:19:19.460 --> 00:19:23.620
[Guest]: She's from Bhopal, and she was in college in Indore.

00:19:23.620 --> 00:19:26.060
[Guest]: And I met her at a very interesting time.

00:19:26.060 --> 00:19:30.740
[Guest]: She was, she's just met someone that she liked on Instagram, who happened to be live in the

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:31.740
[Guest]: same city.

00:19:31.740 --> 00:19:37.140
[Guest]: And she was going on her like, the very first date of her life with this man.

00:19:37.140 --> 00:19:39.500
[Guest]: And I happened to be there in her hostel room at this moment.

00:19:39.500 --> 00:19:43.460
[Guest]: And like, this is the most like, important moment in her life, because she's trying to

00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:49.700
[Guest]: decide what she must wear for her first date with this man that she likes a lot.

00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:51.300
[Guest]: And she had only three options.

00:19:51.300 --> 00:19:55.700
[Guest]: And that I can't remember the third, but they were something that like Katy Perry had worn

00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:58.580
[Guest]: the previous day or Selena Gomez had worn on her first date.

00:19:58.580 --> 00:20:01.540
[Guest]: And so she was like, so she chose Selena Gomez's outfit.

00:20:01.540 --> 00:20:05.420
[Amit Varma]: So you get small town knockoffs of this, which people buy?

00:20:05.420 --> 00:20:06.420
[Guest]: Yes.

00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:12.060
[Guest]: And it was actually a nice white shirt, such as the one I'm wearing, because obviously,

00:20:12.060 --> 00:20:15.820
[Guest]: this is a, it's always a great outfit, but that was more surprising.

00:20:15.820 --> 00:20:19.740
[Guest]: But the more time I spent with 18 year olds in places like that, I realized that it's

00:20:19.740 --> 00:20:23.820
[Guest]: actually pretty usual for them, they may not have to think of Deepika Padukone at all,

00:20:23.820 --> 00:20:24.820
[Amit Varma]: because they have the option.

00:20:24.820 --> 00:20:25.820
[Amit Varma]: They can go straight to Kim Kardashian.

00:20:25.820 --> 00:20:26.820
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:27.820
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:20:27.820 --> 00:20:30.660
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so your second chapter is about, you know, another fascinating character called

00:20:30.660 --> 00:20:33.380
[Amit Varma]: Mohin Khan, who teaches English.

00:20:33.380 --> 00:20:37.980
[Amit Varma]: And you know, again, he is someone who is not even from a family where English is spoken,

00:20:37.980 --> 00:20:41.820
[Amit Varma]: rather he serves those families in various ways.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:45.820
[Amit Varma]: And he overcomes the class difference, takes an English class, because he views it as a

00:20:45.820 --> 00:20:50.540
[Amit Varma]: ticket to another world, it's an aspirational thing, and in a sense, even a ticket to perhaps

00:20:50.540 --> 00:20:55.900
[Amit Varma]: this cultural world of Americana and the internet and so on.

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:59.340
[Amit Varma]: And he learns that and at the end of his first course, he's immediately made the teacher

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:07.260
[Amit Varma]: and he you know, sort of starts teaching English and, and I found that chapter very fascinating.

00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:12.180
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there's one paragraph, which is really interesting, and I'll just again, take the

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:16.860
[Amit Varma]: liberty of quoting that and it's full where you, after you speak about the whole ecosystem

00:21:16.860 --> 00:21:22.980
[Amit Varma]: of language classes, you write, quote, the version of English they speak with colleagues,

00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:27.180
[Amit Varma]: waiters, customer care executives, will define the future of the language in this country.

00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:31.740
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, the future of English worldwide, with India expected to have the largest number

00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:36.180
[Amit Varma]: of English speakers in the world in the next 10 years, overtaking the US, the English they

00:21:36.180 --> 00:21:40.740
[Amit Varma]: speak will be the English of the future, close quote.

00:21:40.740 --> 00:21:44.100
[Amit Varma]: And the English they speak is, in a sense, a very functional sort of English where you're

00:21:44.100 --> 00:21:45.540
[Amit Varma]: kind of getting by.

00:21:45.540 --> 00:21:50.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's also, it has signaling value, it has functional value, and, and that's pretty

00:21:50.120 --> 00:21:51.120
[Amit Varma]: much it.

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:57.040
[Amit Varma]: And that's, that's a big, how big was English in small town India, where you did your stories?

00:21:57.040 --> 00:22:03.260
[Guest]: I think this was the most richest of all the worlds that I tried to describe in the book

00:22:03.260 --> 00:22:08.500
[Guest]: through the various characters and, and I think that I was able to capture because of

00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:16.540
[Guest]: the limits of word length sector, only a part of this because English was huge.

00:22:16.540 --> 00:22:17.700
[Guest]: Everyone wanted to learn it.

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:20.300
[Guest]: Everyone had a very distinct opinion on it.

00:22:20.300 --> 00:22:26.660
[Guest]: There was a large amount of like politics being played over it, especially in the in

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:28.020
[Guest]: the Hindi belt.

00:22:28.020 --> 00:22:35.740
[Guest]: And it just seemed like, like, even in the in the lives of everyone else that I cover,

00:22:35.740 --> 00:22:38.900
[Guest]: English played a part, you know, how they saw it, the relationship with it, if they

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:40.780
[Guest]: were using it, if they were not using it.

00:22:40.780 --> 00:22:45.340
[Guest]: And so I think that it was it was really big.

00:22:45.340 --> 00:22:48.860
[Amit Varma]: Was your speaking English something that put you in a pedestal in the eyes of these guys?

00:22:48.860 --> 00:22:52.460
[Amit Varma]: Like, would they have given you the same access if say you were a Hindi journalist for a Hindi

00:22:52.460 --> 00:22:53.460
[Amit Varma]: newspaper?

00:22:53.460 --> 00:23:00.420
[Guest]: I sat in this spoken English class for at least on and off for at least three months.

00:23:00.420 --> 00:23:05.620
[Guest]: And I wasn't allowed to say a word, forget a sentence, because I would have given myself

00:23:05.620 --> 00:23:10.260
[Guest]: away and then like, like everyone else around me would have felt uncomfortable.

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:15.540
[Guest]: So yes, it was, in some sense, it did stop me from interviewing those kids, because Mohin

00:23:15.540 --> 00:23:17.660
[Guest]: Khan asked me not to speak.

00:23:17.660 --> 00:23:25.300
[Guest]: But yes, I mean, especially with him, I think he felt really connected to me because I was,

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:32.620
[Guest]: he really values a really small set of people with whom he can speak English in a, in a

00:23:32.620 --> 00:23:35.900
[Guest]: fluent way, unlike with the students, and I was one of them.

00:23:35.900 --> 00:23:43.820
[Guest]: So we remain in touch and he, you know, he, I think most of our conversations happened

00:23:43.820 --> 00:23:48.580
[Guest]: in a mix of Hindi and English, but he kept bringing up how much he, he valued the fact

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:54.620
[Guest]: that I was, I was there with him to like, practice his fluent English.

00:23:54.620 --> 00:23:59.020
[Amit Varma]: And just tangentially moving away from a bit from the book itself to your experience of

00:23:59.020 --> 00:24:04.340
[Amit Varma]: writing it, that, you know, at first, when you approach these people, and you started

00:24:04.340 --> 00:24:08.980
[Amit Varma]: interacting with them, they must have had sort of performative selves in front of you

00:24:08.980 --> 00:24:14.180
[Amit Varma]: where they either trying to impress you or whatever, and then gradually they get comfortable

00:24:14.180 --> 00:24:19.140
[Amit Varma]: and they let their guard down and they just themselves and how was this process and how

00:24:19.140 --> 00:24:24.500
[Amit Varma]: how was your awareness of it influencing what went on?

00:24:24.500 --> 00:24:29.260
[Guest]: In some sense, because these were young men, and I, in some cases, I wasn't that much older

00:24:29.260 --> 00:24:30.900
[Guest]: to them.

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:38.140
[Guest]: There was, some of them kept trying to impress me in one way or the other, throughout.

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:43.660
[Guest]: So I don't think that that stopped being the case in some of the, in some cases, especially

00:24:43.660 --> 00:24:50.260
[Guest]: with the Mr. Jharkhand turned aspiring Bollywood superstar, he was just from the first time

00:24:50.260 --> 00:24:54.700
[Guest]: I met him, he just, he was vulnerable and honest, and he decided to like, you know,

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:59.660
[Guest]: just tell me everything, whether it was embarrassing, or it was silly, or, you know, it made him

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:00.700
[Guest]: look bad.

00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:08.260
[Guest]: So there were some people like that and, and especially in the case of the BJP member,

00:25:08.260 --> 00:25:14.180
[Guest]: the BJP, he was the most difficult for me to crack because he wanted to present an image.

00:25:14.180 --> 00:25:20.580
[Guest]: And so no matter what I said, he would just try to like sound aggressive or tell me stories

00:25:20.580 --> 00:25:25.980
[Guest]: of great swagger and importance.

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:29.900
[Guest]: And so I think that was one of the hardest stories for me to report because it took so

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:35.020
[Guest]: many, like meetings over so many months for me to like have a real conversation with him.

00:25:35.020 --> 00:25:39.620
[Amit Varma]: Could that be because like maybe the Mr. Jharkhand guy, because of the class difference, he just

00:25:39.620 --> 00:25:44.140
[Amit Varma]: already put you on a pedestal and you're not someone he's, you know, who is not from the

00:25:44.140 --> 00:25:46.180
[Amit Varma]: same society as him almost.

00:25:46.180 --> 00:25:48.780
[Amit Varma]: And therefore he felt comfortable in opening up to you.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:55.540
[Amit Varma]: But the guy who worked in the BJP was much closer to being from a similar sort of background

00:25:55.540 --> 00:25:58.060
[Amit Varma]: is in fact, your background was pretty similar to him.

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:00.700
[Guest]: You mentioned at one point, yes, yes and no.

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:06.060
[Guest]: I think it was not just class, but also worldviews and ideologies.

00:26:06.060 --> 00:26:10.420
[Guest]: Because when I meet for the same chapter, when I meet a 19 year old member of Bajrang

00:26:10.420 --> 00:26:16.780
[Guest]: Dal in Meerut, he, he comes from a very different social background as well, but he's very hostile

00:26:16.780 --> 00:26:17.780
[Guest]: to me.

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:22.380
[Guest]: And, you know, I have to do a lot of convincing for this guy to talk to me and still to remain

00:26:22.380 --> 00:26:23.380
[Amit Varma]: suspicious.

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:32.180
[Guest]: But I suppose, yes, class was always there, like in the case of the Mr. Jharkhand.

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:36.020
[Guest]: He had never spoken to a woman before.

00:26:36.020 --> 00:26:40.820
[Guest]: And even the participants, even the female participants in the Ram shows that he had

00:26:40.820 --> 00:26:45.660
[Guest]: begun to do wouldn't talk to him because he didn't speak good enough English for them.

00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:48.860
[Guest]: So he did feel left out a lot.

00:26:48.860 --> 00:26:53.780
[Guest]: And I think we came to a point where I was meeting him so often that it seemed to him

00:26:53.780 --> 00:26:59.660
[Guest]: that we were dating, which was really odd because, you know, I would buy him coffee

00:26:59.660 --> 00:27:01.860
[Guest]: and I would ask him questions and he would answer.

00:27:01.860 --> 00:27:07.940
[Guest]: I was taking notes most of the time, but, but he had never like been with a woman in

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:08.940
[Guest]: that way.

00:27:08.940 --> 00:27:13.020
[Amit Varma]: So, and also I'm guessing he had no exposure to journalism of the sort that you were doing

00:27:13.020 --> 00:27:14.020
[Guest]: where you write.

00:27:14.020 --> 00:27:18.660
[Guest]: No, I actually, there's one thing that I decided to do pretty early on, which is to explain

00:27:18.660 --> 00:27:20.140
[Guest]: to them at great length what I was doing.

00:27:20.140 --> 00:27:23.780
[Guest]: So I kept bringing up the fact that this book was now, you know, one third done or one fourth

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:26.340
[Guest]: done and that I was doing meeting these other people.

00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:31.900
[Guest]: And I spoke to them about the importance of their stories and what they meant in a way

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:34.460
[Guest]: that was accessible to them.

00:27:34.460 --> 00:27:38.340
[Guest]: But still, as you said, I mean, they couldn't have understood fully what I was trying to

00:27:38.340 --> 00:27:39.340
[Guest]: do.

00:27:39.340 --> 00:27:43.580
[Guest]: And at some point he asked me if I was his girlfriend and broke my heart, but I had to

00:27:43.580 --> 00:27:48.020
[Guest]: tell him that I wasn't and he mustn't think that and we must keep meeting.

00:27:48.020 --> 00:27:51.460
[Guest]: This was like, so the thing is, I wanted to be their friend.

00:27:51.460 --> 00:27:56.180
[Guest]: I was not, it was never completely an interview with any of these people because I spoke about

00:27:56.180 --> 00:27:57.180
[Guest]: myself.

00:27:57.180 --> 00:27:58.180
[Guest]: They spoke to me about themselves.

00:27:58.180 --> 00:28:03.740
[Guest]: It was more conversation, but at the same time, I think that it, for some time he remained

00:28:03.740 --> 00:28:07.820
[Guest]: hurt and then we got back to the routine.

00:28:07.820 --> 00:28:14.100
[Amit Varma]: And there's that classic journalist dilemma there that when you do a story on someone

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:18.220
[Amit Varma]: at some level, you're using them as instrumental to your purposes.

00:28:18.220 --> 00:28:22.580
[Amit Varma]: And at the other level, you also want to relate to them as human beings and friends.

00:28:22.580 --> 00:28:25.580
[Guest]: And was this something you thought about or something that was difficult?

00:28:25.580 --> 00:28:31.420
[Guest]: I did constantly because there was this power imbalance and there were so many additional

00:28:31.420 --> 00:28:37.500
[Guest]: tensions because of this like male female thing, especially because I was the only woman

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:41.220
[Guest]: in their lives and, you know, in this way, you know, outside of their families with whom

00:28:41.220 --> 00:28:45.940
[Guest]: they were meeting, they were having coffee with, they were sometimes I traveled with

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:46.940
[Guest]: them.

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:51.980
[Guest]: Sometimes I followed them across cities and obviously it made them wonder why I was so

00:28:51.980 --> 00:28:52.980
[Guest]: obsessed with them.

00:28:52.980 --> 00:28:54.940
[Guest]: I was so interested in their lives.

00:28:54.940 --> 00:28:59.420
[Guest]: It happened to me more than once that someone that I was following in this manner asked

00:28:59.420 --> 00:29:03.700
[Guest]: me if that when was, when is our next date or something?

00:29:03.700 --> 00:29:06.000
[Guest]: And so I had to explain again.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:11.420
[Guest]: So, but I know, I guess, but thankfully these conversations spanned years.

00:29:11.420 --> 00:29:17.060
[Guest]: So I think towards the end, they kind of got it and we remained friends and based like,

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:23.220
[Guest]: you know, I think the most important thing to do is to also tell them a lot about myself.

00:29:23.220 --> 00:29:27.900
[Guest]: And I would talk about just daily lives, you know, the way that we did before this, starting

00:29:27.900 --> 00:29:31.340
[Guest]: this podcast, like, you know, I woke up and did this and did that to my parents or my

00:29:31.340 --> 00:29:32.940
[Guest]: sisters or whatever.

00:29:32.940 --> 00:29:35.020
[Guest]: And that did make them feel a little more.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:36.020
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:29:36.020 --> 00:29:39.060
[Amit Varma]: And I guess as long as you were completely upfront with them at the start, then that

00:29:39.060 --> 00:29:40.300
[Amit Varma]: helps you get over the thing.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:43.620
[Amit Varma]: You know that you're not being deceptive in any way, even if they, even if yes, they are

00:29:43.620 --> 00:29:47.220
[Amit Varma]: instrumental to your story, but they know that you're very clear about what you're doing.

00:29:47.220 --> 00:29:48.220
[Guest]: So, yes.

00:29:48.220 --> 00:29:51.540
[Guest]: So, I mean, this took me about three years to report.

00:29:51.540 --> 00:29:54.300
[Guest]: I got married in the, in the middle of it.

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:58.220
[Guest]: And I told most of them that this was happening and they had, they felt really connected.

00:29:58.220 --> 00:29:59.220
[Guest]: They advised me.

00:29:59.220 --> 00:30:03.180
[Guest]: They asked me about the man's background and they checked him out on Facebook, of course.

00:30:03.180 --> 00:30:05.180
[Guest]: Did they approve?

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:06.180
[Guest]: Some of them approved.

00:30:06.180 --> 00:30:08.940
[Guest]: Some of them said that, you know, I should, marriage is a very important institution and

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:11.540
[Guest]: I must know that this is the right man.

00:30:11.540 --> 00:30:17.140
[Guest]: And some of them like patronized about like the values of marriage and like, you know,

00:30:17.140 --> 00:30:19.860
[Guest]: living a more responsible life from now on.

00:30:19.860 --> 00:30:23.980
[Guest]: Because I, because I mean, obviously they thought I was a weirdo, like being a woman

00:30:23.980 --> 00:30:29.180
[Guest]: and like being in all sorts of strange places at all sorts of like strange hours, asking

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:30.180
[Guest]: strange questions.

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:34.780
[Guest]: So, when I decided to get married, I thought that maybe this is when I become like normal.

00:30:34.780 --> 00:30:37.660
[Amit Varma]: It's very interesting when you, you know, talking about marriage and strong opinions

00:30:37.660 --> 00:30:38.660
[Amit Varma]: on it.

00:30:38.660 --> 00:30:41.380
[Amit Varma]: One of the most fascinating parts of your book, which made me really sit up with my

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:45.620
[Amit Varma]: eyes wide open, was in that English class where you're sitting with Mohin Khan and he

00:30:45.620 --> 00:30:49.220
[Amit Varma]: organizes this debate on arranged marriage versus love marriage between the girls and

00:30:49.220 --> 00:30:50.340
[Amit Varma]: the boys.

00:30:50.340 --> 00:30:54.260
[Amit Varma]: And it ends into a screaming match where they're shouting at each other, like it's Bhakts versus

00:30:54.260 --> 00:30:55.260
[Amit Varma]: Congresses on Twitter.

00:30:55.260 --> 00:30:59.140
[Amit Varma]: You know, that was the kind of feel I got from your writing, where people who wouldn't

00:30:59.140 --> 00:31:02.900
[Amit Varma]: talk across the aisle, like the girls were almost segregated before the class and brought

00:31:02.900 --> 00:31:06.940
[Amit Varma]: in later when the teacher came because they didn't want to intermingle, are suddenly just

00:31:06.940 --> 00:31:09.700
[Amit Varma]: screaming at each other and getting personal.

00:31:09.700 --> 00:31:10.700
[Amit Varma]: What was that like?

00:31:10.700 --> 00:31:17.040
[Guest]: It's another thing that we don't understand, but the whole like, you know, think about

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:23.940
[Guest]: love and dating and sex and marriage just, there's so much anxiety and dilemma about

00:31:23.940 --> 00:31:24.940
[Guest]: that.

00:31:24.940 --> 00:31:29.580
[Guest]: It's the case of women, because I made friends with some of these girls from the English

00:31:29.580 --> 00:31:32.460
[Guest]: class and wow, their lives were very complicated.

00:31:32.460 --> 00:31:38.180
[Guest]: I mean, each of them sort of knew that she had to ultimately go through arranged marriage

00:31:38.180 --> 00:31:44.100
[Guest]: set by family, but they wanted before that to get as much out of life as they could.

00:31:44.100 --> 00:31:49.300
[Guest]: So they had three or four boyfriends off Facebook who they were like hiding from each other.

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:52.900
[Guest]: And there were like three or four phones on which they were like playing this game.

00:31:52.900 --> 00:31:55.860
[Guest]: And yeah, it was quite amazing.

00:31:55.860 --> 00:31:59.060
[Amit Varma]: And I think it's one of the reader questions we have, and I was going to ask you at the

00:31:59.060 --> 00:32:03.100
[Amit Varma]: end of the episode, but since it's just come up, that your book is all about guys.

00:32:03.100 --> 00:32:06.300
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's with the exception of Richa Singh in one chapter.

00:32:06.300 --> 00:32:09.620
[Amit Varma]: But I think that's kind of natural, because if you're looking at young India, a lot of

00:32:09.620 --> 00:32:14.860
[Amit Varma]: what you visibly see is these disaffected young men who don't have jobs and the women

00:32:14.860 --> 00:32:21.180
[Amit Varma]: are sort of in the background already suppressed, not so many options open to them.

00:32:21.180 --> 00:32:27.700
[Amit Varma]: Not such, not really strong actors in their own lives as so many of the men are.

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:30.820
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you thought about during the book, or you just went with what came

00:32:30.820 --> 00:32:34.060
[Amit Varma]: naturally that these are the, you know, subjects of my stories?

00:32:34.060 --> 00:32:38.620
[Guest]: No, I wanted this to be out the mainstream, because I think that as a journalist, and

00:32:38.620 --> 00:32:42.780
[Guest]: I had been working as a journalist for many years before I began this, I was interested

00:32:42.780 --> 00:32:47.100
[Guest]: in stories of resistance against what was this mainstream, which was like male and young

00:32:47.100 --> 00:32:53.140
[Guest]: and in some sense more North Indian than South Indian, more upper caste than anything else.

00:32:53.140 --> 00:32:58.540
[Guest]: And so I just wanted to understand who these people are, that oppress like every, like

00:32:58.540 --> 00:33:02.380
[Guest]: so many kinds of so many groups of people.

00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:07.940
[Guest]: And the other thing I thought about was that I didn't want to make any effort finding anyone.

00:33:07.940 --> 00:33:12.940
[Guest]: I was like, what if I just arrived in a place, walked on a street and start talking to people?

00:33:12.940 --> 00:33:14.860
[Guest]: I will that that's the kind of thing that I wanted to do.

00:33:14.860 --> 00:33:19.900
[Guest]: It was like, what is really like, who are these, like, you know, the most visible people

00:33:19.900 --> 00:33:26.460
[Guest]: if you leave your home or hotel in a in a North Indian town, a young man, yes, a young

00:33:26.460 --> 00:33:31.060
[Guest]: man, they have little to do, they're, they're literally all over the place, they are very

00:33:31.060 --> 00:33:32.060
[Guest]: eager to talk.

00:33:32.060 --> 00:33:33.500
[Guest]: And I just, I'd never spoken to them.

00:33:33.500 --> 00:33:37.620
[Guest]: So I wanted to ask them what, what was going on in their lives, a friend of mine who just

00:33:37.620 --> 00:33:42.140
[Amit Varma]: came back from Bihar painted this picture to me where he said that whenever he'd get

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:46.380
[Amit Varma]: out at a railway station or walk out on the street, he'd see this almost surreal sight

00:33:46.380 --> 00:33:50.980
[Amit Varma]: of many, many, many young men just standing there doing just standing there.

00:33:50.980 --> 00:33:51.980
[Guest]: Yes.

00:33:51.980 --> 00:33:57.100
[Guest]: One of the things I did reporting from Haryana a couple of months ago is just take random

00:33:57.100 --> 00:34:02.780
[Guest]: photos of public spaces, you know, streets or railway stations or like, bus stands, whatever.

00:34:02.780 --> 00:34:09.980
[Guest]: And I'd like with no frame in mind or any like, structural ideas.

00:34:09.980 --> 00:34:13.100
[Guest]: And I came back home and I started looking at the photos and like counting the number

00:34:13.100 --> 00:34:14.820
[Guest]: of men that are there in every photo.

00:34:14.820 --> 00:34:18.420
[Guest]: And it's amazing because all of these like pictures are full of men, they may be like

00:34:18.420 --> 00:34:24.020
[Guest]: one or two women, and all of these places that I went to for reporting in police stations

00:34:24.020 --> 00:34:25.020
[Guest]: and courts.

00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:27.220
[Guest]: And so that that does tell you something.

00:34:27.220 --> 00:34:30.660
[Guest]: And I think it's those men that I wanted to speak to.

00:34:30.660 --> 00:34:34.180
[Amit Varma]: It's kind of a haunting image, just men just standing there hundreds of young men not doing

00:34:34.180 --> 00:34:36.420
[Amit Varma]: anything and that that kind of makes you worried.

