00:35:52.180 --> 00:35:58.180
[Amit Varma]: I now want to talk about the second part of your book, which really has two chapters dealing

00:35:58.180 --> 00:36:01.380
[Amit Varma]: on how people deal with their anger.

00:36:01.380 --> 00:36:06.300
[Amit Varma]: And the first of them I was sort of very struck by because your two main characters in that

00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:11.620
[Amit Varma]: one of them is someone who breaks up love jihads in Jharkhand, I think, right?

00:36:11.620 --> 00:36:12.620
[Guest]: In Meerut.

00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:16.780
[Amit Varma]: In Meerut, who breaks up love jihads and the other is a Gaurakshak.

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:21.820
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, these are not the two only sort of angry people you came across.

00:36:21.820 --> 00:36:26.180
[Amit Varma]: There's a lot of anger out there, which you describe throughout your book.

00:36:26.180 --> 00:36:31.360
[Amit Varma]: But these are at the same time fairly representative of two of the typical directions that the

00:36:31.360 --> 00:36:37.940
[Amit Varma]: anger goes in that it finds an outlet in tribalism, almost sort of instinctive tribalism, where

00:36:37.940 --> 00:36:43.300
[Amit Varma]: in these two cases, it becomes a question of Hindu pride and all Muslims are bad.

00:36:43.300 --> 00:36:48.380
[Amit Varma]: And it finds these different kinds of outlets in the case of one interreligious couplings

00:36:48.380 --> 00:36:51.700
[Amit Varma]: and the other cows.

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:58.420
[Amit Varma]: And how widespread is this and you know, did you feel that this is the most natural outlet

00:36:58.420 --> 00:36:59.420
[Amit Varma]: for their anger?

00:36:59.420 --> 00:37:00.420
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:37:00.420 --> 00:37:07.700
[Guest]: I mean, the one of the people that I describe in the book is, is very different, though.

00:37:07.700 --> 00:37:14.780
[Guest]: I mean, he's middle class, he's a very respectable member of the BGP, he's, you know, he's, he's

00:37:14.780 --> 00:37:20.820
[Guest]: a part of the discussions on elections and election management, etc.

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:25.100
[Guest]: And, and he's very different in that, you know, when I started speaking to him, he's

00:37:25.100 --> 00:37:32.340
[Guest]: he's talking about big, grand things and not like beating up people or, or breaking up.

00:37:32.340 --> 00:37:38.260
[Guest]: Imagine Love Jihad, he's talking about Gandhi and Nehru and, you know, the imbalances of

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:46.420
[Guest]: power in in the world and like, civilizations like histories and, and how to rethink them.

00:37:46.420 --> 00:37:48.340
[Guest]: And so we keep having these conversations.

00:37:48.340 --> 00:37:55.100
[Guest]: And I keep thinking that, that maybe something will come out of this, but, but towards the

00:37:55.100 --> 00:37:59.260
[Guest]: end, as it becomes more and more open with me, he, he brings up some of the same things

00:37:59.260 --> 00:38:05.860
[Guest]: that these Bajrang Dal karikartas in Meerut, or the Gaurakshaks in Haryana bring up later,

00:38:05.860 --> 00:38:10.860
[Guest]: which is, you know, that, that Hindus have been treated badly in this country, or, you

00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:16.020
[Guest]: know, Muslims are reproducing too much, or, you know, Dalits are taking all the jobs,

00:38:16.020 --> 00:38:21.060
[Guest]: or, you know, the, you know, the women just don't know their place in the society anymore.

00:38:21.060 --> 00:38:22.740
[Guest]: So that's the same sort of stuff.

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:29.340
[Guest]: And I think that those are the same set of things that I kept hearing from, like young

00:38:29.340 --> 00:38:36.900
[Guest]: men, at least like across North India, no matter, you know, what their social background.

00:38:36.900 --> 00:38:43.140
[Guest]: And so yes, I was pretty widespread, I tried to choose people who had more to say about

00:38:43.140 --> 00:38:48.980
[Guest]: that whose stories were more complicated than, or like, I could find something about them

00:38:48.980 --> 00:38:51.780
[Guest]: that wasn't obvious in these statements.

00:38:51.780 --> 00:38:57.180
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I'd always thought that tribalism, or the tribal instinct, in a sense is ingrained

00:38:57.180 --> 00:38:58.180
[Amit Varma]: within us.

00:38:58.180 --> 00:39:02.700
[Amit Varma]: And it's just that as societies progress more and more, you know, culture mitigates that

00:39:02.700 --> 00:39:09.220
[Amit Varma]: and there's no reason to be tribal and that instinct is sort of mitigated simply by culture

00:39:09.220 --> 00:39:11.580
[Amit Varma]: and enlightenment values and so on.

00:39:11.580 --> 00:39:16.740
[Amit Varma]: But what seems to be happening here is that tribal instincts evolved in times of scarcity.

00:39:16.740 --> 00:39:21.060
[Amit Varma]: And if you are living in a time of a scarcity of some kind, in this kinds, whether it's

00:39:21.060 --> 00:39:24.580
[Amit Varma]: of jobs, or whether it's of different kinds of opportunities.

00:39:24.580 --> 00:39:29.540
[Guest]: Women, in some of the cases, they can't, in places like Haryana, they can't find women

00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:30.540
[Amit Varma]: to marry.

00:39:30.540 --> 00:39:34.180
[Amit Varma]: So they become very angry with, like one of the quotes I noted down from that chapter

00:39:34.180 --> 00:39:39.340
[Amit Varma]: is the gentleman in Karnal who told you, quote, since every girl in Karnal has a boyfriend,

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:41.620
[Amit Varma]: I don't know whether I will ever be married.

00:39:41.620 --> 00:39:42.620
[Guest]: Yes.

00:39:42.620 --> 00:39:43.620
[Guest]: Unquote.

00:39:43.620 --> 00:39:44.620
[Guest]: I mean, look at the sex ratio of Haryana.

00:39:44.620 --> 00:39:48.900
[Guest]: It will be very difficult for him to find a bride and he's concerned about that.

00:39:48.900 --> 00:39:52.220
[Guest]: And that makes him very angry and he has to find an outlet.

00:39:52.220 --> 00:39:55.660
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, are these people also in a sense India's incels?

00:39:55.660 --> 00:39:57.060
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, yes.

00:39:57.060 --> 00:40:01.820
[Amit Varma]: You know, and are these therefore scarcities of jobs, scarcity of sexual opportunities

00:40:01.820 --> 00:40:08.180
[Amit Varma]: leading to this anger, which obviously will then take a tribal form, it's almost inevitable.

00:40:08.180 --> 00:40:12.500
[Amit Varma]: And would you then say that is something that's gotten worse over the last few years?

00:40:12.500 --> 00:40:16.260
[Amit Varma]: And it actually seems to be happening worldwide in different forms.

00:40:16.260 --> 00:40:19.220
[Amit Varma]: And if so, is it going to continue getting worse?

00:40:19.220 --> 00:40:23.980
[Guest]: So first of all, I wish there was only simply a lack of opportunities that drove these,

00:40:23.980 --> 00:40:29.140
[Guest]: you know, thousands of men across India to murder and mime people.

00:40:29.140 --> 00:40:30.340
[Guest]: But it's something deeper than that.

00:40:30.340 --> 00:40:38.080
[Guest]: I mean, I have now reported on Gaurakshaks alone for some years, and I've met so many

00:40:38.080 --> 00:40:39.080
[Guest]: kinds of Gaurakshaks.

00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:43.460
[Guest]: You know, there are people who are middle-aged, you know, doctors and there are 22-year-olds

00:40:43.460 --> 00:40:48.220
[Guest]: who have ice cream shops and they're, you know, this guy is in the book as an insurance

00:40:48.220 --> 00:40:49.220
[Guest]: salesman.

00:40:49.220 --> 00:40:51.980
[Guest]: So it's not always that they don't have anything to do.

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:56.900
[Guest]: I think the source of their anger sometimes is deeper.

00:40:56.900 --> 00:41:02.820
[Guest]: Sometimes it is not how they are doing, but how people who shouldn't be, you know, doing

00:41:02.820 --> 00:41:05.260
[Guest]: that well are doing well or doing better than them.

00:41:05.260 --> 00:41:11.340
[Guest]: Like in the case of this chap in Meerut, he's angry at how, you know, the young Muslim men

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:19.060
[Guest]: in his neighborhood have been able to build houses or date attractive women that he would

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:20.060
[Guest]: he would like to date.

00:41:20.060 --> 00:41:23.340
[Guest]: So he's angry about all those things.

00:41:23.340 --> 00:41:32.820
[Guest]: And you know, in some cases, it is about jobs, but it's not always about their own lack of

00:41:32.820 --> 00:41:35.540
[Guest]: opportunities or jobs or upward mobility.

00:41:35.540 --> 00:41:40.460
[Guest]: They're equally angry about the fact that the people who should have remained below

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:49.940
[Guest]: them have now like surpassed them in either income or education or attraction to women

00:41:49.940 --> 00:41:51.020
[Guest]: really can be anything.

00:41:51.020 --> 00:41:57.460
[Guest]: And then, and especially in some of the cases in the more patriarchal belts of North India,

00:41:57.460 --> 00:42:05.020
[Guest]: I think Haryana for one, there was this deep rooted anxiety about how their families weren't

00:42:05.020 --> 00:42:09.220
[Guest]: respecting them, you know, that their mothers and their bhabis and whatever, you know, the

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:14.380
[Guest]: women in the family or the older male members of the family was not giving them the kind

00:42:14.380 --> 00:42:18.360
[Guest]: of izzat that like a young man at that age should receive.

00:42:18.360 --> 00:42:24.420
[Guest]: So that also like played into this anger that some of them did turn card carrying Gaurakshaks

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:28.460
[Guest]: because of that, because they felt like if they did go out on these raids night after

00:42:28.460 --> 00:42:33.740
[Guest]: night carrying revolvers and coming back with these amazing stories and WhatsApp photographs

00:42:33.740 --> 00:42:41.540
[Guest]: of rescued cows and beaten up Muslim cattle smugglers, then they will regain that kind

00:42:41.540 --> 00:42:46.180
[Guest]: of respect in the eyes of their own families, their own neighborhoods, their own local police

00:42:46.180 --> 00:42:50.740
[Guest]: thana, their local RSS shakhas, etc.

00:42:50.740 --> 00:42:54.700
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of the scary part of this, like, in a sense, if you have anger, if you're

00:42:54.700 --> 00:42:58.540
[Amit Varma]: driven to these tribalistic narratives, it would be okay if you express that on the internet

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:02.620
[Amit Varma]: and you told people on Twitter, but in your everyday life, you're forced to behave normally,

00:43:02.620 --> 00:43:03.620
[Amit Varma]: because that's a society.

00:43:03.620 --> 00:43:07.460
[Amit Varma]: But in the case of all of these people that you've written about, and that you mentioned

00:43:07.460 --> 00:43:12.900
[Amit Varma]: in that chapter, they are incentivized to actually act out their violence, because that's

00:43:12.900 --> 00:43:16.220
[Amit Varma]: a way of raising their status within their in group.

00:43:16.220 --> 00:43:21.220
[Amit Varma]: So it's not only that they feel this resentment, but there is actually, they raise their own

00:43:21.220 --> 00:43:26.940
[Amit Varma]: social status by, in the case of the gentlemen in Meerut, just beating up couples on Valentine's

00:43:26.940 --> 00:43:33.540
[Amit Varma]: Day, in the case of the cow rakshaks, just doing whatever it takes to sort of fight something

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:35.780
[Guest]: which is really imaginary, in a sense.

00:43:35.780 --> 00:43:41.700
[Guest]: And at the same time, and I didn't, I hadn't fully even explored it by the time I wrote

00:43:41.700 --> 00:43:46.500
[Guest]: the last draft, but the levels to which, because this is only happening right now, the levels

00:43:46.500 --> 00:43:55.940
[Guest]: to which that anger is channeled institutionally, I mean, even in 2014 or 15, when I was reporting

00:43:55.940 --> 00:44:06.540
[Guest]: this book, I found several, you know, smaller groups of Hindu interest cropping up everywhere,

00:44:06.540 --> 00:44:12.660
[Guest]: not just the usual RSS and Bajrang Dal and VHP, but Akhil Bharat, this and that, or,

00:44:12.660 --> 00:44:15.180
[Guest]: you know, Meerut Shetty, this and that.

00:44:15.180 --> 00:44:17.580
[Amit Varma]: Or the kind of people who killed Kalburgi and...

00:44:17.580 --> 00:44:25.460
[Guest]: Yes, but now these groups are really multiplying, mushrooming, whatever you call it, like,

00:44:25.460 --> 00:44:31.700
[Guest]: you can go on Facebook, type any city, the smallest of towns in India, and it'll have

00:44:31.700 --> 00:44:33.780
[Guest]: at least like a dozen of these groups.

00:44:33.780 --> 00:44:38.260
[Guest]: I just keep doing this from time to time, just to like, you know, track the progress

00:44:38.260 --> 00:44:39.380
[Guest]: of this trend.

00:44:39.380 --> 00:44:40.380
[Guest]: But the smallest of towns...

00:44:40.380 --> 00:44:41.380
[Amit Varma]: No, you don't.

00:44:41.380 --> 00:44:42.380
[Amit Varma]: You're a closet bigot.

00:44:42.380 --> 00:44:43.380
[Amit Varma]: You are a fangirl.

00:44:43.380 --> 00:44:49.700
[Guest]: They will have Akhil Bharat, blah, blah, blah, and there will be like dozens of these groups.

00:44:49.700 --> 00:44:54.220
[Guest]: Some of these like members will be common, but most of them will, each of them will be

00:44:54.220 --> 00:45:01.020
[Guest]: able to attract hundreds of people who are very active on on Facebook, each of them wants

00:45:01.020 --> 00:45:07.580
[Guest]: to like, you know, raise his profile on Facebook and WhatsApp through whatever, whatever, you

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:12.220
[Guest]: know, fake news they can spread or whatever, like, real time violence they can inflict

00:45:12.220 --> 00:45:14.260
[Guest]: and then take photos of and post.

00:45:14.260 --> 00:45:17.660
[Amit Varma]: And that's scary, because it's, it's mind blowingly scary, because it's a vicious circle

00:45:17.660 --> 00:45:22.340
[Amit Varma]: in that case, because if you want to belong to a group in a small town, these are kind

00:45:22.340 --> 00:45:27.740
[Amit Varma]: of the groups you'll be drawn towards, because, you know, and it just perpetuates itself.

00:45:27.740 --> 00:45:33.460
[Guest]: And yes, but because because what happened, for example, in the case of the disruption

00:45:33.460 --> 00:45:40.180
[Guest]: of namaz in Gurgaon, was that when I spoke to some of these young men who had disrupted

00:45:40.180 --> 00:45:46.700
[Guest]: the namaz, they said that they'd initially been trained as wrestlers in their villages,

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:55.580
[Guest]: RSS shakha, but it was too, but when RSS was a very moderate and modest reference point

00:45:55.580 --> 00:45:57.980
[Guest]: for them, you know, like a group for them.

00:45:57.980 --> 00:46:02.060
[Guest]: So they had been looking for more and more aggressive leaders and organizations with

00:46:02.060 --> 00:46:06.740
[Guest]: which to associate themselves, like one of them told me that he has now linked himself

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:11.020
[Guest]: to this man is a long name Swami Paramanand something something.

00:46:11.020 --> 00:46:17.500
[Guest]: And whose claim to fame is that he has built an army of 1500 people in UP who will fight

00:46:17.500 --> 00:46:19.860
[Guest]: ISIS.

00:46:19.860 --> 00:46:25.700
[Guest]: And like all they do all day is just like, you know, do arms training and, you know,

00:46:25.700 --> 00:46:29.780
[Guest]: engage in this very alarmist view of the future of India.

00:46:29.780 --> 00:46:34.220
[Guest]: And because RSS, for this guy, RSS was just not giving him the kind of like opportunities

00:46:34.220 --> 00:46:39.460
[Guest]: for brazen violence against whoever is his enemy, as he's desired.

00:46:39.460 --> 00:46:47.180
[Guest]: So he has to leave that umbrella and choose like more and more extremist, like validation

00:46:47.180 --> 00:46:51.180
[Guest]: from the Hindu interest umbrella, so it's almost a race to the bottom.

00:46:51.180 --> 00:46:54.580
[Guest]: Yes, it was a race to the bottom, which is what scared me that we keep thinking that,

00:46:54.580 --> 00:46:59.540
[Guest]: you know, RSS is like taking over in India, and we are all doomed, but there are worse

00:46:59.540 --> 00:47:00.540
[Amit Varma]: entities.

00:47:00.540 --> 00:47:04.540
[Amit Varma]: I keep talking about the Jan Sang Kam BJP that every leader made the previous guy look

00:47:04.540 --> 00:47:05.540
[Unknown]: moderate.

00:47:05.540 --> 00:47:11.340
[Amit Varma]: So Atal Bihari made Shyama Prasad look moderate and then Advani to Atal Bihari and Modi to

00:47:11.340 --> 00:47:15.580
[Amit Varma]: Advani and Adityanath to Modi and somebody will one day horror of horrors make Adityanath

00:47:15.580 --> 00:47:16.580
[Guest]: look moderate.

00:47:16.580 --> 00:47:22.740
[Guest]: I went to a press conference of these all self-styled extreme Hindu leaders and they

00:47:22.740 --> 00:47:29.380
[Guest]: said, you know, Yogi kuch nahi hai, Modi has failed us, Advani to bahut budha ho gaya hai

00:47:29.380 --> 00:47:34.260
[Guest]: and take any name, they were like, Togadia has vanished after fear.

00:47:34.260 --> 00:47:39.420
[Guest]: So it's us and it is going to be our revolvers and lattes.

00:47:39.420 --> 00:47:43.100
[Amit Varma]: Which means inevitably, they will never feel satisfied with any of the people who go into

00:47:43.100 --> 00:47:48.380
[Amit Varma]: politics because those guys will be moderated by necessary compromises and therefore, eventually

00:47:48.380 --> 00:47:50.980
[Amit Varma]: these people will want to take the law into their own hands.

00:47:50.980 --> 00:47:51.980
[Guest]: They are.

00:47:51.980 --> 00:47:54.460
[Guest]: I mean, that happened in the case of the Namaz in Gurgaon.

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:55.460
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:47:55.460 --> 00:47:59.100
[Amit Varma]: And that Swamiji's paramilitary force of 1500 people should just be airdropped to actually

00:47:59.100 --> 00:48:01.660
[Amit Varma]: fight ISIS in Syria, that would be nice.

00:48:01.660 --> 00:48:06.220
[Amit Varma]: But they will fight like Namazis in Gurgaon.

00:48:06.220 --> 00:48:13.100
[Amit Varma]: Which is even worse, or infidels like us who are born Hindu but dare to be secular or whatever

00:48:13.100 --> 00:48:15.860
[Amit Varma]: it is that we are.

00:48:15.860 --> 00:48:20.620
[Amit Varma]: And all of these people naturally are not just bigoted, but they're also deeply misogynist.

00:48:20.620 --> 00:48:27.980
[Amit Varma]: And that makes the fifth chapter of your book on Richa Singh from Allahabad extremely fascinating

00:48:27.980 --> 00:48:33.580
[Amit Varma]: where you describe about how Allahabad University is sort of a hotbed of young male violence

00:48:33.580 --> 00:48:40.580
[Amit Varma]: almost my words, not yours, which and no woman has ever stood for elections there because

00:48:40.580 --> 00:48:44.180
[Amit Varma]: it's completely unthinkable because in the power structures, they are just so suppressed

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:47.620
[Amit Varma]: that they're not even seen in public during elections because there are violent young

00:48:47.620 --> 00:48:48.620
[Guest]: men roaming around.

00:48:48.620 --> 00:48:52.020
[Amit Varma]: Quote unquote, anything can happen, anything can happen.

00:48:52.020 --> 00:48:56.860
[Amit Varma]: And this young girl called Richa Singh decides that she is going to stand for president of

00:48:56.860 --> 00:49:00.340
[Amit Varma]: the Allahabad University Students Union.

00:49:00.340 --> 00:49:07.500
[Amit Varma]: And, and you describe the responses against her and did you sort of feel that her standing

00:49:07.500 --> 00:49:14.100
[Amit Varma]: up against the patriarchy, as she puts it, is sort of an aberration, or is it a sign

00:49:14.100 --> 00:49:15.900
[Amit Varma]: that things might be changing?

00:49:15.900 --> 00:49:27.420
[Guest]: An aberration, I think, because as I when I'm winding up in the last in the conclusion,

00:49:27.420 --> 00:49:31.020
[Guest]: when I try to catch up with what was going on in Allahabad student politics, in the time

00:49:31.020 --> 00:49:36.740
[Guest]: that I hadn't checked, few women had followed up, they like the couple of elections that

00:49:36.740 --> 00:49:41.580
[Guest]: happened after hers were even more violent, and women had stayed away, etc, etc.

00:49:41.580 --> 00:49:45.500
[Amit Varma]: So, and she also got co opted into the system joined the Samajwadi party.

00:49:45.500 --> 00:49:50.580
[Amit Varma]: She got an MLA ticket that she went by the way, no, she lost, because that was the that

00:49:50.580 --> 00:49:51.580
[Amit Varma]: was a sweep.

00:49:51.580 --> 00:49:57.980
[Guest]: But she's quite active in the Samajwadi election schemes right now, like, you know, she was

00:49:57.980 --> 00:50:03.980
[Guest]: very active behind the scenes of the Phool Phool election or by elections.

00:50:03.980 --> 00:50:11.220
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know how cynical to feel about her being with the Samajwadi party, but I

00:50:11.220 --> 00:50:14.940
[Amit Varma]: wonder what else she could have done.

00:50:14.940 --> 00:50:19.860
[Amit Varma]: But what was telling to me is your detailed descriptions of the rage that the young men

00:50:19.860 --> 00:50:25.380
[Amit Varma]: of Allahabad expressed towards most of which was because she was a woman and not because

00:50:25.380 --> 00:50:29.540
[Amit Varma]: she was from the other party or whatever, yes, the threats that she got, for example,

00:50:29.540 --> 00:50:33.820
[Amit Varma]: that if you come out of your hostel, we will rape you and so on.

00:50:33.820 --> 00:50:39.140
[Amit Varma]: Just and do you think that rage would be the same all across small town India because of

00:50:39.140 --> 00:50:40.340
[Amit Varma]: how misogynist we are?

00:50:40.340 --> 00:50:43.900
[Guest]: No, of course, it's more North Indian than anything, I think that I would be joking if

00:50:43.900 --> 00:50:50.500
[Guest]: I said that this level of patriarchy, misogyny, and I shouldn't even say North India, I mean,

00:50:50.500 --> 00:50:53.580
[Guest]: some parts are worse than the others.

00:50:53.580 --> 00:51:01.340
[Guest]: Like I, I grew up in a very different North India than the one that I encountered in Allahabad.

00:51:01.340 --> 00:51:05.220
[Guest]: Because you know, you're talking about decades and decades of that kind of male entitlement

00:51:05.220 --> 00:51:11.660
[Guest]: that you know, you feel that women shouldn't even come out at the time of student elections.

00:51:11.660 --> 00:51:17.020
[Guest]: So it was, it did blow me away in the worst kinds of ways.

00:51:17.020 --> 00:51:20.660
[Amit Varma]: And would you say this kind of entitlement is actually worse than previous generations?

00:51:20.660 --> 00:51:25.100
[Amit Varma]: Because these young people have been exposed to what's happening around the world, and

00:51:25.100 --> 00:51:28.180
[Amit Varma]: they can't they can see it, but they can't actually touch any of it themselves.

00:51:28.180 --> 00:51:30.260
[Amit Varma]: And that leads to greater anger.

00:51:30.260 --> 00:51:31.260
[Guest]: Yes.

00:51:31.260 --> 00:51:37.220
[Guest]: And a lot of the anger that I described in the preceding chapter, young angry men, the

00:51:37.220 --> 00:51:41.740
[Guest]: you know, a lot of their anger was also against women.

00:51:41.740 --> 00:51:47.620
[Guest]: In most of these cases, they were angry that the women around them just weren't behaving

00:51:47.620 --> 00:51:52.940
[Guest]: the way that the women should do on in some cases, simply that they had no hope of finding

00:51:52.940 --> 00:51:58.620
[Guest]: a wife or in the case of the love, you know, the Bajrang Dal Karkarta in Meerut, after

00:51:58.620 --> 00:52:05.660
[Guest]: a whole day of like being hateful about everyone else, to me, he, I go back home, I go back

00:52:05.660 --> 00:52:07.460
[Guest]: to my hotel, he goes back home.

00:52:07.460 --> 00:52:12.020
[Guest]: And he sends me a message on WhatsApp, saying something.

00:52:12.020 --> 00:52:18.780
[Guest]: And I, I look at his display photo, and it's a red teddy bear or something.

00:52:18.780 --> 00:52:22.860
[Guest]: And I was like, Wow, you're, dude, you're a softie.

00:52:22.860 --> 00:52:26.460
[Guest]: For all your you know, I'm going to like kill and finish all my enemies.

00:52:26.460 --> 00:52:27.980
[Amit Varma]: The metrosexual love jihad warrior.

00:52:27.980 --> 00:52:28.980
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:52:28.980 --> 00:52:29.980
[Guest]: The sensitive side.

00:52:29.980 --> 00:52:30.980
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:52:30.980 --> 00:52:33.980
[Amit Varma]: He will beat up the couple and then he will cry for them.

00:52:33.980 --> 00:52:38.020
[Amit Varma]: And then he will put makeup on the cops is sorry.

00:52:38.020 --> 00:52:42.920
[Amit Varma]: Moving on to sort of the third section of your book, which was also kind of fascinating

00:52:42.920 --> 00:52:48.820
[Amit Varma]: and entirely expected in terms of that was a part of the book, which was sort of least

00:52:48.820 --> 00:52:52.140
[Amit Varma]: surprising to me in a sense, I mean, a lot of things about your book were eye opening

00:52:52.140 --> 00:52:53.140
[Amit Varma]: to me.

00:52:53.140 --> 00:52:57.940
[Amit Varma]: But you know, the fact that at one point in the book, you say, it seemed much easier to

00:52:57.940 --> 00:53:02.500
[Amit Varma]: become successful feeding on other people's dreams and following your own.

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:05.700
[Amit Varma]: And you know, just to take a slight digression to economics, this is something like Jagdish

00:53:05.700 --> 00:53:10.420
[Amit Varma]: Bhagwati once said was a difference between China and India, where he said that in China,

00:53:10.420 --> 00:53:12.220
[Amit Varma]: people tend to be profit seeking.

00:53:12.220 --> 00:53:15.620
[Amit Varma]: But in India, people tend to be rent seeking.

00:53:15.620 --> 00:53:19.900
[Amit Varma]: And I actually have a theory that this is partly because of the structures of our government,

00:53:19.900 --> 00:53:24.900
[Amit Varma]: where government is so all powerful and so pervasive, that the easiest way to make money

00:53:24.900 --> 00:53:29.500
[Amit Varma]: is actually to feed off that power in some way to either rent seek or to essentially

00:53:29.500 --> 00:53:34.060
[Amit Varma]: play a zero sum game where you're exploiting someone and not a positive sum game where

00:53:34.060 --> 00:53:38.180
[Amit Varma]: you're trying to do something which will create value in somebody's life and like even the

00:53:38.180 --> 00:53:42.460
[Guest]: English teachers, for example, the English teachers are playing that positive and the

00:53:42.460 --> 00:53:46.700
[Amit Varma]: fixer, Mr. Prasad are playing that positive game where they're trying to do things for

00:53:46.700 --> 00:53:50.580
[Amit Varma]: other people and they're both benefiting, but a lot of the people in this last section

00:53:50.580 --> 00:53:55.260
[Amit Varma]: of your book, the scammers, which I think is much more representative of India and not

00:53:55.260 --> 00:54:00.460
[Amit Varma]: just small town India today, but India, since I have, you know, in all the years that I've

00:54:00.460 --> 00:54:05.460
[Amit Varma]: spent here, is that people have this scammy mentality of how can I exploit someone and

00:54:05.460 --> 00:54:11.540
[Amit Varma]: make money rather than how can I sort of add value to the world and if anything, I'd imagine

00:54:11.540 --> 00:54:17.540
[Amit Varma]: that is probably getting worse because of the scarcities that we sort of discussed that

00:54:17.540 --> 00:54:24.460
[Amit Varma]: it's just this attitude that the one way to get rich or to make money is to exploit somebody

00:54:24.460 --> 00:54:29.380
[Amit Varma]: else, you know, where if you're not scamming somebody, you're getting scammed, that kind

00:54:29.380 --> 00:54:34.340
[Amit Varma]: of mentality. And I also felt that, you know, the people you mentioned in the first part

00:54:34.340 --> 00:54:38.460
[Amit Varma]: of your book, the guys who are making something out of their lives, Vinay Singhal or Witty

00:54:38.460 --> 00:54:45.380
[Amit Varma]: Feed or Moin Khan, the English teacher, are in one sense the outliers, you know, in a

00:54:45.380 --> 00:54:49.100
[Amit Varma]: sense, they're not all like that. It would be the survivorship bias to say that that's

00:54:49.100 --> 00:54:53.820
[Amit Varma]: your typical young Indian. They are the lucky guys who despite who actually sort of found

00:54:53.820 --> 00:54:59.420
[Amit Varma]: that way. But I would imagine that your typical young Indian would fall more in the people

00:54:59.420 --> 00:55:03.340
[Amit Varma]: you describe in your last couple of chapters, the scamsters who are either scamming or getting

00:55:03.340 --> 00:55:05.180
[Guest]: scammed. Would you agree with that?

00:55:05.180 --> 00:55:10.820
[Guest]: Absolutely, absolutely. And I think that's that you couldn't have been more right. You

00:55:10.820 --> 00:55:16.140
[Guest]: know, when we were talking about this earlier, but a million people enter the job market

00:55:16.140 --> 00:55:22.020
[Guest]: every month, and we don't have any estimates, but maybe anywhere between 10,000 and 25,000

00:55:22.020 --> 00:55:27.140
[Guest]: people find jobs in the formal economy, we have a very vast informal economy in which

00:55:27.140 --> 00:55:34.840
[Guest]: hundreds of 1000s of people must go as delivery boys and drivers and small factory workers,

00:55:34.840 --> 00:55:40.220
[Guest]: it still leaves out hundreds of 1000s of people who are like, even in this vast informal economy,

00:55:40.220 --> 00:55:46.740
[Guest]: I didn't understand that that world really well. And so, you know, I mean, what I wanted

00:55:46.740 --> 00:55:53.500
[Guest]: to do for the last chapter was actually just try to be a job seeker in the entry level

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:57.900
[Guest]: market and try to get a job. And, and this is what what happened. And most of the jobs

00:55:57.900 --> 00:56:06.020
[Guest]: that I found that I could be offered did require me to pull some or the other kind of con.

00:56:06.020 --> 00:56:11.860
[Guest]: And so in a sense, yes, those are the majority of like, you know, the young Indians about

00:56:11.860 --> 00:56:14.940
[Guest]: whom I was trying to write this book.

00:56:14.940 --> 00:56:18.380
[Amit Varma]: And you can't even blame them or make a you know, judge them for it. Because you know,

00:56:18.380 --> 00:56:23.260
[Amit Varma]: as you say in that chapter, quote, as young men with no prospects, they are the biggest

00:56:23.260 --> 00:56:27.780
[Amit Varma]: victims and the whole world is a big scam. Stop quote, which is kind of how they see

00:56:27.780 --> 00:56:31.380
[Amit Varma]: themselves. They're saying the world is a scam. We are victims. Why should we not scam

00:56:31.380 --> 00:56:36.500
[Amit Varma]: others? It's a zero sum game. You know, you you just, you try to get on top of it.

00:56:36.500 --> 00:56:42.660
[Guest]: Yes, I don't think that many of them start out by with the scammy mentality at all. Some

00:56:42.660 --> 00:56:47.980
[Guest]: of them do. Some of them are really good at this job. They're extremely good at Jugaad.

00:56:47.980 --> 00:56:51.820
[Guest]: You know, you show them a scam, and they're like, you know, pick up tricks of trade and

00:56:51.820 --> 00:56:56.580
[Guest]: matter of hours, they're very good at building a network, you know, drawing like resources

00:56:56.580 --> 00:57:04.020
[Guest]: from other like, stakeholders in the business, you know, they can they can really scale up

00:57:04.020 --> 00:57:10.500
[Guest]: from 4000 pounds to 40,000 pounds in a week. So I also met some amazing like talent in

00:57:10.500 --> 00:57:16.060
[Guest]: the world of call center scams. But the majority of like the soldiers, the call center executives

00:57:16.060 --> 00:57:22.300
[Guest]: that I met, didn't start out by buying been trying to being scammy. In fact, for so many

00:57:22.300 --> 00:57:26.780
[Guest]: of them like drop out after the first day of training or after they were giving a script

00:57:26.780 --> 00:57:33.980
[Guest]: or something because they just they just can't do it. Every day, I receive an email from

00:57:33.980 --> 00:57:37.860
[Guest]: an ex-scammer because obviously they can't go to the police because like they're so afraid

00:57:37.860 --> 00:57:43.300
[Guest]: of whatever and they will describe to me the entire like modes of operation of their companies

00:57:43.300 --> 00:57:50.220
[Guest]: addresses, like you know, the the location details of the masterminds the ways to like

00:57:50.220 --> 00:57:54.940
[Guest]: bust those companies and what's more important their justifications for why they did it to

